Good Morning Detectives from the Special crime Preventions Unit on Friday searched the Nairobi home of Migori Governor Okoth Obado in search for his gun license. The police failed to recover the firearm license during the police operation that lasted close to two hours. Here are the stories making headlines in the Star this Saturday morning. Senior lawyers enlist to join DPP as special prosecutors in corruption cases In a bid to secure successful prosecutions, the Director of Public Prosecutions Noordin Haji is reviewing applications by some high profile lawyers who want to be special prosecutors. Last month, Haji invited applications for Pre-qualification of Lawyers for Provision of Legal Services for the period of 2018-2020. More than 100 law firms applied to be on the DPP's side and the shortlisting is going. _____________________________________________________ Handshake has strengthened Parliament's oversight role: MPs The unity pact entered between President Uhuru Kenyatta and Nasa leader Raila Odinga, commonly known as 'handshake' has enhanced Parliament's oversight role, MPs claim. Last Tuesday, National Assembly Speaker Justin Muturi told the House that Cabinet Secretaries are not above the law and should honour invites from House committees to respond to questions. Muturi maintained that CSs have no excuse not to appear before the committees and warned that stern action will be taken against those who fail to honour the invites. _____________________________________________________ Gakuo's family wants appeal to proceed despite his demise The Family of the late former Town Clerk John Gakuo wants an appeal challenging his conviction over the shs 283 million cemetery scandal proceed to full hearing despite his demise. Lawyer Assa Nyakundi told Anti-corruption High court Judge Hedwig Ong’undi that they wish to continue with the case and have his name cleared. Nyakundi maintained that Gakuo was not corrupt and he did not deserve the three year sentence handed to him over the purchase of cemetery land in Nairobi. _____________________________________________________ Confusion at City Hall after expiry of county executives' contracts Confusion has engulfed City Hall following the expiry of executive’s contracts, threatening to paralyse its operations. The assembly’s Budget and Appropriations committee said the executive held a vital role in key county decisions. This was after a member of the committee; Kayole South MCA Fredrick Okeyo revealed that the executives’ contracts expired last week. _____________________________________________________ Chris Mureithi talks, clients smile and the money flows From being “indulged in the foreplay that leads to being fired” — otherwise known as being put on a performance improvement plan — to sitting on a panel with the same manager at a national conference, Chris Mureithi is a good example of how far resilience can take you. But how did the once-struggling sales officer become a sought-after keynote speaker? The Star caught up with Mureithi, a personal development and training consultant who describes himself as an investor in happy endings. _____________________________________________________ For more on these stories and others, keep browsing the Star website for the latest news making headlines across Kenya and around the world. To get the Breakfast Briefing right into your inbox every morning, click here for a free subscription. Click here for the latest political news